        <div class="comment">
        <p class="metadata">Posted by Matthew Weier O'Phinney (matthew) on 2009-05-17T20:08:28.000+0000</p> 
        <div class="body">
            <p>I would argue that Zend_Validate should not extend Zend_Validate_Abstract, as it is meant for creating validation chains and does not offer any concrete validation of its own.</p>

        </div>
    </div>
        <div class="comment">
        <p class="metadata">Posted by Thomas Weidner (thomas) on 2009-06-20T03:51:07.000+0000</p> 
        <div class="body">
            <p>I looked again into this issue.</p>

<p>Zend_Validate itself does not validate itself. It is a container for validation where you can attach concrete validators.</p>

<p>As translation must be done by the validator itself (think of values which are integrated into the translated message), there is no need of translation for Zend_Validate itself.</p>

<p>When you need translation for multiple validators set default translation for the abstract class or one of the used validators.</p>

<p>There is no change if you are using validation chain (isValid) or static validation (is). For both you have to attach a concrete validator.</p>

<p>Therefor closing this issue as won't fix.
When you are missing a concrete feature feel free to add a new issue describing what's missing.</p>

